Carregando os dados

df <- read_excel("DADOS_BR_SB.xlsx") |> select(Date,BBAS3_SB,IBOVC_SB) |> drop_na()
# Banco do Brasil SA (BBAS3)
bbas <- xts(as.numeric(df$BBAS3_SB), order.by=as.Date(df$Date))
# Bovespa Index (IBOV)
ibov <- xts(as.numeric(df$IBOVC_SB), order.by=as.Date(df$Date))

ACF e PACF

BBAS3

ggAcf(bbas, lag.max=12 )

ggPacf(bbas, lag.max=12)

IBOV

ggAcf(ibov, lag.max=12)

ggPacf(ibov, lag.max=12)

Estacionaridade

BBAS3

Transformando em Log e teste para estacionaridade. Pelo teste de Augmented Dickey-Fuller, rejeitamos a hipÃ³tese nula para sÃ©rie estacionÃ¡ria. AlÃ©m disso, ndiffs() retona um nÃºmero inteiro indicando quantas diferenÃ§as sÃ£o requeridas para estacionaridade.

lbbas <- log(bbas)
adf.test(lbbas)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  lbbas
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.9857, Lag order = 18, p-value = 0.5844
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
ndiffs(lbbas,test="adf")
## Warning: The chosen unit root test encountered an error when testing for the second difference.
## From ur.df(): 
## NAs in y.
## 
## 1 differences will be used. Consider using a different unit root test.
## [1] 1

Assim, fazendo a primeira diferenÃ§a e realizando os mesmos testes anteriores. Adicionalmente, incluÃ­mos o teste KPSS que Ã© usado com a hipÃ³tese nula de uma raiz estacionÃ¡ria contra uma alternativa de raiz unitÃ¡ria. ConcluÃ­mos portanto que a sÃ©rie em primeira diferenÃ§a do log() Ã© estacionÃ¡ria.

dlbbas<- na.omit(100*diff(lbbas))

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
ggAcf(dlbbas, lag.max=12, main ='')
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: main

ggPacf(dlbbas, lag.max=12, main ='')
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: main

adf.test(dlbbas)
## Warning in adf.test(dlbbas): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  dlbbas
## Dickey-Fuller = -17.979, Lag order = 18, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
ndiffs(dlbbas,test="adf")
## [1] 0
ndiffs(dlbbas,test="kpss")
## [1] 0

IBOV

Transformando em Log e teste para estacionaridade. Pelo teste de Augmented Dickey-Fuller, rejeitamos a hipÃ³tese nula para sÃ©rie estacionÃ¡ria. AlÃ©m disso, ndiffs() retona um nÃºmero inteiro indicando quantas diferenÃ§as sÃ£o requeridas para estacionaridade.

libov <- log(ibov)
adf.test(libov)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  libov
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.1163, Lag order = 18, p-value = 0.5291
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
ndiffs(libov,test="adf")
## Warning: The chosen unit root test encountered an error when testing for the second difference.
## From ur.df(): 
## NAs in y.
## 
## 1 differences will be used. Consider using a different unit root test.
## [1] 1

Assim, fazendo a primeira diferenÃ§a e realizando os mesmos testes anteriores. Adicionalmente, incluÃ­mos o teste KPSS que Ã© usado com a hipÃ³tese nula de uma raiz estacionÃ¡ria contra uma alternativa de raiz unitÃ¡ria. ConcluÃ­mos portanto que a sÃ©rie em primeira diferenÃ§a do log() Ã© estacionÃ¡ria.

dlibov<- na.omit(100*diff(libov))

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
Acf(dlibov, lag.max=12, main ='')
Pacf(dlibov, lag.max=12, main ='')

adf.test(dlibov)
## Warning in adf.test(dlibov): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  dlibov
## Dickey-Fuller = -16.618, Lag order = 18, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
ndiffs(dlibov,test="adf")
## [1] 0
ndiffs(dlibov,test="kpss")
## [1] 0

Melhor modelo

BBAS3

Usamos o critÃ©rio informacional para melhor fittar um modelo ARIMA. Para isso usamos a funÃ§Ã£o auto.arima() que retorna o melhor modelo ARIMA de acordo com o valor AIC ou BIC. A funÃ§Ã£o realiza uma pesquisa sobre o modelo possÃ­vel dentro das restriÃ§Ãµes de ordem fornecidas. PorÃ©m, a âfitâ indicado nÃ£o se mantÃ©m consistente dependendo da forma de aproximaÃ§Ã£o da funÃ§Ã£o. A aproximaÃ§Ã£o que produz estimativas significantes Ã© quando aplicamos o âfitâ na diferenÃ§a do log. Assim, iremos utilizar o melhor modelo como ARIMA(1,1,1).

#auto.arima(bbas)
auto.arima(lbbas)
## Series: lbbas 
## ARIMA(1,1,0) with drift 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1  drift
##       0.0058  7e-04
## s.e.  0.0130  3e-04
## 
## sigma^2 = 0.0006922:  log likelihood = 13045.67
## AIC=-26085.33   AICc=-26085.33   BIC=-26065.29
auto.arima(lbbas,max.p=12,max.q=12,max.d=2,stepwise=FALSE,approx=FALSE, trace=F)
## Series: lbbas 
## ARIMA(3,1,2) with drift 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1     ar2      ar3     ma1      ma2  drift
##       -0.1915  0.7119  -0.0132  0.1978  -0.7370  7e-04
## s.e.   0.1526  0.1436   0.0145  0.1522   0.1409  3e-04
## 
## sigma^2 = 0.0006914:  log likelihood = 13051.03
## AIC=-26088.07   AICc=-26088.05   BIC=-26041.31
auto.arima(dlbbas)
## Series: dlbbas 
## ARIMA(1,0,0) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1    mean
##       0.0058  0.0656
## s.e.  0.0130  0.0345
## 
## sigma^2 = 6.922:  log likelihood = -14028.13
## AIC=28062.26   AICc=28062.26   BIC=28082.3
auto.arima(dlbbas,max.p=12,max.q=12,max.d=2,stepwise=FALSE,approx=FALSE, trace=F)
## Series: dlbbas 
## ARIMA(1,0,4) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1     ma1      ma2      ma3      ma4    mean
##       -0.7986  0.8049  -0.0107  -0.0254  -0.0346  0.0637
## s.e.   0.1243  0.1247   0.0168   0.0173   0.0139  0.0330
## 
## sigma^2 = 6.913:  log likelihood = -14022.36
## AIC=28058.72   AICc=28058.74   BIC=28105.47
eq1 <- arima(dlbbas, order=c(1,0,1), include.mean = TRUE, method= "ML")
plot(eq1$residuals)
abline(h = mean(eq1$residuals)+1.96*sd(eq1$residuals), col='red', lty=2)
abline(h = mean(eq1$residuals)-1.96*sd(eq1$residuals), col='red', lty=2)

jarque.bera.test(eq1$residuals)
## 
##  Jarque Bera Test
## 
## data:  eq1$residuals
## X-squared = 8354.9, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16

IBOV

Usamos o critÃ©rio informacional para melhor fittar um modelo ARIMA. Para isso usamos a funÃ§Ã£o auto.arima() que retorna o melhor modelo ARIMA de acordo com o valor AIC ou BIC. A funÃ§Ã£o realiza uma pesquisa sobre o modelo possÃ­vel dentro das restriÃ§Ãµes de ordem fornecidas. Como comparaÃ§Ã£o temos que tentar usar o critÃ©rio informacional com descuido gera interpretaÃ§Ãµes imprecisas. ConcluÃ­mos que o melhor modelo Ã© ARIMA(1,1,0).

auto.arima(ibov)
## Series: ibov 
## ARIMA(0,1,2) 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1     ma2
##       -0.0801  0.0465
## s.e.   0.0130  0.0131
## 
## sigma^2 = 888347:  log likelihood = -48603.62
## AIC=97213.25   AICc=97213.25   BIC=97233.28
auto.arima(libov,max.p=12,max.q=12,max.d=2,stepwise=FALSE,approx=FALSE)
## Series: libov 
## ARIMA(1,1,0) 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1
##       -0.0290
## s.e.   0.0131
## 
## sigma^2 = 0.0002943:  log likelihood = 15559.61
## AIC=-31115.22   AICc=-31115.22   BIC=-31101.86
auto.arima(dlibov,max.p=12,max.q=12,max.d=2,stepwise=FALSE,approx=FALSE)
## Series: dlibov 
## ARIMA(1,0,0) with zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1
##       -0.0290
## s.e.   0.0131
## 
## sigma^2 = 2.943:  log likelihood = -11514.19
## AIC=23032.37   AICc=23032.37   BIC=23045.73
eq2 <- arima(libov, order=c(1,1,1), include.mean = TRUE, method= "ML")
plot(eq2$residuals)
abline(h = mean(eq2$residuals)+1.96*sd(eq2$residuals), col='red', lty=2)
abline(h = mean(eq2$residuals)-1.96*sd(eq2$residuals), col='red', lty=2)

jarque.bera.test(eq2$residuals)
## 
##  Jarque Bera Test
## 
## data:  eq2$residuals
## X-squared = 12981, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16

Estimando Recursivamente

BBAS3

O melhor modelo escolhido inicialmente nÃ£o Ã© possivel ser estimado por OLS. Assim vamos considerar o ARIMA(1,1,0) e estimando o modelo por OLS

df_recursivo <- cbind(dlbbas,Lag(dlbbas))
colnames(df_recursivo) <- c("dlbbas", "dlbbas_lag")
eq1r <- lapply(seq(10, length(dlbbas)), function(x) lm(dlbbas ~ dlbbas_lag, data = df_recursivo[1:x, ]))
summary(eq1r[[1]])
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = dlbbas ~ dlbbas_lag, data = df_recursivo[1:x, ])
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.1484 -1.5255 -0.2015  0.7579  3.4312 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)   0.4639     0.6217   0.746    0.480
## dlbbas_lag   -0.4270     0.2380  -1.794    0.116
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.865 on 7 degrees of freedom
##   (1 observation deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.315,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.2171 
## F-statistic: 3.219 on 1 and 7 DF,  p-value: 0.1159
length(eq1r)
## [1] 5870
# storing all coefficients
all_intercepts <- unlist(sapply(1:length(eq1r),function(j) eq1r[[j]]$coefficients[1]))
all_slopes<-unlist(sapply(1:length(eq1r),function(j) eq1r[[j]]$coefficients[2]))
all_slopes[1]  # slope from the first regression
## dlbbas_lag 
## -0.4269905
# storing sd
sd_intercepts <- unlist(sapply(1:length(eq1r),function(j) summary(eq1r[[j]])$coefficients[3]))
sd_slopes<-unlist(sapply(1:length(eq1r),function(j) summary(eq1r[[j]])$coefficients[4]))
sd_slopes[1]  # slope sd from the first regression 
## [1] 0.2379895
# plotting the coefficients
par(mfrow = c(2,1))

plot.zoo(cbind(all_intercepts, 
               all_intercepts+ sd_intercepts*1.96, 
               all_intercepts-sd_intercepts*1.96), 
         plot.type = "single", 
         main = "Recursive estimation - intercept", 
         ylab = "", xlab = "",
         col = c(1,2,2))


plot.zoo(cbind(all_slopes, 
               all_slopes+ sd_intercepts*1.96, 
               all_slopes-sd_intercepts*1.96), 
         plot.type = "single", 
         main = "Recursive estimation - phi", 
         ylab = "", xlab = "",
         col = c(1,2,2))

# CUSUM 
cusum <- strucchange::efp(dlbbas ~ Lag(dlbbas), type = "Rec-CUSUM")
plot(cusum, ylab = "")

# CUSUMQ
residrls2 <- eq1$residuals^2 
cusumq <- cumsum(c(0, residrls2))/sum(residrls2)
plot(cusumq, type = "l", main = "Recursive CUSUMQ test", ylab = "")

# Prediction of Dollar
bbas_ff <- c()
h <- 7
for(i in 0:(h-1)){
  eq1 <- Arima(bbas[1:(length(bbas)-h+i),], order = c(1,1,0))   
  aux_eq1_f <- forecast(eq1, h = 1)$mean  
  bbas_ff <- rbind(bbas_ff, aux_eq1_f)
}


bbas_f <- bbas[(length(bbas)-(h-1)):length(bbas)]

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot.zoo(cbind(bbas_f, bbas_ff,
               bbas_ff + 1.96*sd(bbas_ff),
               bbas_ff - 1.96*sd(bbas_ff)), 
         plot.type = "single",
         col = c(1,2,3,3), 
         ylab = "",
         xlab = "", 
)
legend("top", inset=c(0,0),  horiz=TRUE, cex = .8,
       y.intersp = 1, lty = 1, bty = "n", 
       legend = c("Observed", "Forecast", "LS and LI"), col = c(1,2,3,3))
